## Personal blog for Kyle Werner

Personal blog at [wernull.com](https://wernull.com) — tube amplifiers and tech.
Built with Jekyll 4, hosted on AWS S3 + CloudFront.

Local development runs in **Docker** so the native toolchain (Ruby + libvips
for responsive images) doesn't need to be installed or maintained on the host.

### Dev server (Docker)

```bash
docker compose up            # http://localhost:4000 (live-reload enabled)
docker compose up --build    # rebuild the image after changing the Gemfile
docker compose down          # stop
```

The project directory is bind-mounted, so edits to posts, styles, and layouts
reload automatically.

### New post

```bash
docker compose run --rm jekyll rake new_post['Post Title']
```

### Production build

```bash
docker compose run --rm -e JEKYLL_ENV=production jekyll bundle exec jekyll build
```

Output is written to `public/` on the host.

## Deploy

```bash
bash deploy.sh
```

`deploy.sh` builds the site in Docker, then uses the host AWS CLI (profile
`wernull`) to sync `public/` to `s3://wernull.com` and invalidate the two
CloudFront distributions. AWS credentials stay on the host and never enter the
container.

---

## NAM Capture Player

An interactive A/B looper for auditioning the same guitar performance reamped through multiple NAM (Neural Amp Modeler) captures. Readers pick a track (radio button), toggle which of 8 sections loop (checkboxes), and the player stays **on-beat and seamless** as they switch.

### Playback engine

Uses the Web Audio API (not HTML5 `<audio>`) to guarantee **gapless looping + sample-accurate section skipping**. Decodes `.m4a` files to `AudioBuffer`, schedules one 8-second section at a time with a lookahead scheduler, and applies changes at the next downbeat so they're never mid-section or mid-fade.

### Recording & producing audio files

1. Record one DI (clean direct signal) at **120 BPM, 4/4** with a click, arranged as **8 distinct 4-bar sections** (128 beats = 64 seconds total). Land on a clean onset/root at each section boundary so skips don't chop a ringing note.
2. Edit the DI region to start exactly at bar 1, beat 1 (sample 0); trim to exactly 64.000 seconds.
3. Reamp that same DI through each NAM model in your DAW (offline render), which guarantees all captures are sample-aligned and exactly 64 seconds.
4. Level-match the renders (e.g. normalize to ~−16 LUFS) so switching tracks doesn't jump in volume.
5. Export each at 44.1 kHz, encode to **AAC `.m4a` (~160 kbps)** for size + universal browser support.
6. Upload to S3/CloudFront, e.g. `https://wernull.com/audio/amp12/model-name.m4a`.

### Embedding in a post

Add `nam_player` config to the post's frontmatter:

```yaml
nam_player:
  bpm: 120                    # optional (default 120)
  sections: 8                 # optional (default 8)
  bars_per_section: 4         # optional (default 4)
  leadIn: 0                   # optional; 0 = auto-detect AAC encoder priming
  tracks:
    - name: "Model Name 1"
      src: https://wernull.com/audio/ampNN/model1.m4a
    - name: "Model Name 2"
      src: https://wernull.com/audio/ampNN/model2.m4a
```

Then embed the player in the post body:

```liquid
{% include nam-player.html %}
```

For multiple players on one page, pass a different frontmatter key: `{% include nam-player.html key="nam_player_2" %}`.

---

### Notes

- First `docker compose up` builds the image (installs Ruby gems + libvips);
  subsequent runs are fast.
- Ports: `4000` (site), `35729` (live-reload).
- `Gemfile.lock` includes Linux platforms (`x86_64-linux`, `aarch64-linux`) so
  bundler resolves correctly inside the container.
